                                    <h2>
                                        Windows
                                    </h2>
                                    
                                    <h3>Overview</h3>
<br />
You can display additional video sources on the Wall if you have the proper hardware attached to a controller. This is similar to sharing your screen in Meet, but it has a variety of potential applications, including:

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li>Displaying third-party applications that may not work directly in a workspace, such as computer-aided design software.</li>
	<li>Connecting a Cisco Webex Room Kit to make use of intelligent video conferencing.</li>
</ul>
<b>Note</b>: Screens&nbsp;shared via external hardware are only visible from the room they&rsquo;re shared in. This means they are not visible to remote participants in the workspace.

<h3>Requirements</h3>
&nbsp;

<ul>
	<li>Laptop or other device that supports video output to HDMI.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>A video capture device connected to the Wall&rsquo;s controller, such as an HDMI to USB3 converter.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Instructions</h3>
<br />
To display an additional video source on a Wall:
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<ol>
	<li>Enter a workspace on the Wall, either by opening a temporary workspace or sending a workspace to the Wall.</li>
	<li>Connect your video capture device. <b>Note</b>: The Wall client can support up to three devices. However, only one feed can display at a time.</li>
	<li>Tap the <b>Apps</b> icon on the side-panel menu.</li>
    <li>The <b>Apps</b> tray opens. Tap the <b>External A/V</b> icon.</li>
    <li>If you have multiple devices connected, each one&rsquo;s individual video feed displays in the <b>Apps</b> menu. Tap the desired feed. <b>Note</b>:&nbsp;Up to three devices can be supported.</li>
    <li>A window automatically appears over the workspace and displays your video feed on the Wall.</li>
</ol>
<br />
If your video source does not display on the Wall, try the following:
<br />

<ul>
	<li>Unplug the video source from the video capture device, restart the controller, and try again.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Contact Bluescape Support</li>
</ul>
You can move and resize the window of the external video feed on the Wall. In addition, you can take a snapshot of it. Once captured in a workspace, you can easily mark up the image and receive feedback from collaborators. For more information, see <a href="https://support.bluescape.com/BluescapeSupport_Article?a=Taking-a-Snapshot-of-Interactive-Assets" target="_blank">Taking a Snapshot of Interactive Assets</a>.<br />
<br />
<b>Note</b>:&nbsp;Aside from the actions discussed above, you cannot interact with your video feed on the Wall; the Wall simply displays it.
