                                    <h2>Linux</h2>
                                    <p>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                    
                                    <h3>
                                        Overview
                                    </h3>
                                    You can share your screen onto a Wall using your laptop&rsquo;s HDMI port. This is similar to sharing your screen in Meet, but the quality of the screen share is better because it&rsquo;s in High Definition. Anything displayed on your laptop displays on the Wall; the Wall becomes an extension of your laptop&rsquo;s screen. This is useful for displaying third-party applications that may not work directly in the workspace, such as computer-aided design software.<br />
<br />
                                    <h3>
                                        Requirements
                                    </h3>
                                    <p>
                                        Ensure&nbsp;your laptop has an HDMI port. It is often labelled and located on the side of your laptop near the USB port(s).
                                    </p>
                                    <h3>
                                        Instructions
                                    </h3>
To share your screen using HDMI:
                                    <p>
                                        
                                    </p>
<ol>
	<li>&nbsp;Enter a workspace on the Wall, either by opening a temporary workspace or by sending a workspace to the Wall.</li>
	<li>&nbsp;Find the HDMI cable that is connected to the Wall. It is located below, behind, or on the side of the Wall unit.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>&nbsp;Take the free end of the HDMI cable and plug it into the HDMI port on your laptop.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>&nbsp;A window automatically appears over the workspace and displays your computer screen on the Wall.&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
                                    <br />

<p>If your screen does not display on the Wall, try the following options:&nbsp;</p>
                                    <br />

<ul>
	<li>Unplug the HDMI cable from your computer, restart the controller, and try again.</li>
	<li>Verify the HDMI cable is connected through an Inogeni to a USB port on the controller. The Inogeni is an HDMI to USB converter.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Contact your IT department and ensure your computer supports dual monitors.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Contact Bluescape support.</li>
</ul>
                                    <br />
<b>Note</b>: Screens shared via HDMI are only visible from the room they&rsquo;re shared in. This means they are not visible to remote participants in the workspace.<br />
<br />
You can also take a snapshot of your screen when you screen share with HDMI. This is useful when you want to capture High Definition images of your screen. Once captured in a workspace, you can easily mark up the image and receive feedback in Bluescape.

<p><br />
<b>Note</b>: Aside from taking a screenshot, you cannot interact with your laptop&rsquo;s screen on the Wall; the Wall simply displays it.</p>

                                    
